<font color="#FF0000">THOUGHTS</font><br>
<tt>Tue Aug 19 23:47:20 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
John and Cook,<br><br>
You dialog provoked some reflections.<br><br>
If you strip away politics, and get right down to pure motive, I cannot help but draw connections with our revolution against the British. The British overestimated their ability to defeat the colonial revolutionaries, us, and in the face of it all, we utilized guerilla tactics probably learned from Native Americans, against a fossilized military machine that pranced around in senseless formations. We beat the hell out of them, though not without the ebb and flow of of toil and fortune.<br><br>
I feel that at some dark level, the Vietnam War was really a conflict with ourselves, a throwback into our own struggle for independence from a &quot;master&quot;. I respected the enemy, because he was good, real good. So were we, but in a different way.<br><br>
I have no love for the dictatorships we cast as communist, or any dictatorship, for that matter. We cannot forget, however, that many of the respected religious institutions and groups early in this country embraced a communal existence for survival. Some of these continue to this day. This communal way philosophy was much later corrupted as &quot;communist&quot; and subsequently used as an excuse for the monstrosity of inhuman dictatorial control and destruction which we were sworn to fight.<br><br>
George Marden, a Revolutionary War Soldier, lies buried in a small family cemetary on my property behind my house. What I would give for a time machine to get George's view of the Vietnam War and our continued deliberations, 30 years or so hence, and still counting. I wonder what he would say about all this. Were we fools, just foolish, or right on? I don't know. I still just have that old creepy feeling about it all. Nothing yet seems to fit.  
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


